{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565395"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17405"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17405"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.13,0.2,0.12,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10095"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109098"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10095"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91466"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1722"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"8343"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38304"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of progressive sore throat, difficulty swallowing, and noisy breathing. He has been drooling and unable to swallow his saliva. Over the last hour, he has noticed increased shortness of breath with minimal activity. He has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus managed with metformin and is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and is sitting upright, leaning forward. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. He has audible inspiratory stridor and is drooling. His voice is muffled. His neck is tender but not swollen. When asked to lie back to 45 degrees for an ECG, he becomes agitated and his oxygen saturation drops to 88%, which resolves upon sitting upright.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Awake fibreoptic intubation","Lateral neck X-ray","Nebulised adrenaline","Intravenous antibiotics","Examination of oropharynx with tongue depressor"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of acute epiglottitis, including drooling, dysphagia, and respiratory distress. The characteristic tripod position (sitting upright and leaning forward) and stridor suggest significant upper airway compromise. His positional desaturation and increasing respiratory distress indicate imminent airway compromise. Adult epiglottitis can progress rapidly to complete airway obstruction and requires immediate airway management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAwake fibreoptic intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it allows controlled securing of the airway while the patient maintains spontaneous breathing. This should be performed in an operating theatre with surgical backup available for emergency tracheostomy if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral neck X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially showing the classic \u0027thumb sign\u0027 of an enlarged epiglottis, would delay definitive airway management in a patient with signs of impending airway obstruction. Although a lateral X-ray can be performed with the patient sitting upright, any delay in securing the airway in this critically unwell patient is inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExamination of oropharynx with tongue depressor\u003C/strong\u003E is absolutely contraindicated as it may precipitate complete airway obstruction. Visual examination of the epiglottis should only be performed in a controlled setting where immediate airway intervention is possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E may provide temporary relief of symptoms but does not address the underlying problem and may give a false sense of security while the condition continues to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E and corticosteroids should be administered but should not delay definitive airway management. The most common causative organism is \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E type b, although this is less common in adults than children. Diabetes and smoking are risk factors that may complicate the clinical course.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adult epiglottitis requires urgent airway management due to risk of complete airway obstruction.","The classic triad of epiglottitis is drooling, dysphagia, and distress with a characteristic tripod position.","Examination of the throat with a tongue depressor is contraindicated as it may precipitate complete airway obstruction."],"references":["Dowdy RA, Cornelius BW. Medical management of epiglottitis. Anesthesia progress. 2020 Jul 6;67(2):90. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7342809/","O Cathain E, Gaffey MM. Upper Airway Obstruction. [Updated 2022 Oct 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564399/","Eskander A, de Almeida JR, Irish JC. Acute Upper Airway Obstruction. N Engl J Med. 2019 Nov 14;381(20):1940-1949. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1811697. PMID: 31722154. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31722154/","Yiannakis, Constantina P., and Omar J. Hilmi. Surgery. Evaluation and management of acute upper airway obstruction. Surgery; 2024. Available from: https://www.surgeryjournal.co.uk/article/S0263-9319%2824%2900087-5/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-17T15:58:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T15:59:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10095"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109098"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}